A Czech Discovery: An Effective Substance Even in the 'HIV Viruses'
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds capable of moderate the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of this improved substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some medicines already accessible.
The AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, the life of patients may be significantly extended by a mixture of medicines that prevent replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of the experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University shows the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that the substances called metalocarbons have an effect on the albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are made up of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently from all medicines used today, and that is why they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalocarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedra cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are united by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A Traitor and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the protease of HIV, the fractionation of the HIV virus does not occur and no mature, infectious bodies of the virus would be created.
