Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have called for the construction of minarets to be banned and where there is a widespread warning of the supposed Islamization of Europe, John Bowen, an American scholar, has written a detailed and studied report on the possible integration of Muslims (which are actually being integrated) into one of the most openly secular societies on the continent.
Some readers will come to this new book as admirers of the author's latest work "Why French don't Like Headcarves" (2006), an elegant and detailed study of a problem that divided and worried the country for a decade and a half, and whose effects are still perceived today.
Mr Bowen's last book has a broader and more ambitious perspective.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening.
It has been months in mosques, schools and institutes that now provide the 5-6 million Muslims in France what Mr Bowen calls "Islamic spaces".
He is a good listener who reproduces discussions between teachers and students about the questions that interest them most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or in a city (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it legitimate for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to obtain a mortgage?
These are apparently worldly issues, he maintains, things of everyday life, those that concern the media more than political dramas.
The author identifies a new generation of magnets, professors and intellectuals, none of them of fame, with the possible exception of Tariq Ramadán, an Arab Muslim scholar and scholar born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how to be at the same time a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They cannot fully disseminate this argument.
Conservatives only doubt the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists that Mr Bowen interviewed tend to disagree with his Salafi counterparts, supporters of the Purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia, who currently have a small but influential presence among Muslims in Europe.
Bowen thinks that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But adaptation requires mutual concessions.
He questions the extent to which the French political strategists (and the intellectual elite that so fiercely defends secularism) are really committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims probably have a more unfair treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, who have also had to make their historic commitments to secular republicanism.
More than a growing pragmatism, it perceives "a value adjustment".
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, one tends to say "Yes, but not yet."
