Chinese officials have endorsed the policy for their contribution to avoiding critical pressure on their natural resources, while human rights defenders have denounced abuses in the imposition of policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to undergo abortions.
In addition, many couples have had abortions according to the fetus sex, leading to a high unnatural male-woman ratio.
In recent years, demographic officials have gradually softened their position on the single child policy.
In 2004, more exceptions were made to the rule, including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where both husband and wife are single children, and in 2007 many of their hard-line slogans were mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Demographic Research at the University of Beijing, said that central government officials have been discussing recently even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the spouses is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost at night in the morning, the posters that ordered families to have only one child were replaced by copies of regulations detailing who would be suitable for having a second child and how to apply for a permit.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to visit couples in their homes and slide leaflets under the doors.
It has also promised to provide emotional and financial guidance to those who have chosen to have more than one child.
Family planning officials say that the response has been very low.
Disappointment Response
Although rural city officials on the outskirts of Shanghai maintain that they have seen a moderate increase in the requests of couples who want a second child after the campaign is launched, the most urban districts indicate no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, is still receiving only four to five applications per month.
The disappointed Shanghai officials say that, despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to reach only 165,000, slightly higher than in 2009, but less than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Municipality of Caolu in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want more children.
They want to give their first child their best, he said.
Yang Jiawei, aged 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, aged 26, said they would love to have two children and are legally empowered to do so.
But like many Chinese, they have only insufficient health and life insurance provided by the government.
Without a social protection network, they say, that option would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudged the policy of a single child as a matter of rights, Yang said, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant by the couple's first child.
Yeah, they're stealing from us the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just a political issue.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for their doubts.
Wang, the human resources administrator, said he wants a unique child because she was also: "We were the center of our families and we were used to all taking care of us.
We are not used to caring for others and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42 years old, owner of a translation agency, explained it more strongly.
For middle-class parents who reduce the birth rate, he said, it is about having enough success to be selfish.
People between the ages of 20 and 30 grew up seeing their parents' struggle during the first days of China's experiment with capitalism and they don't want that kind of life for themselves, he said.
Even one child requires a lot of time from the parents, he said.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are questions of space, "they have to remodel their apartment," and the strategic has to "have a curriculum prepared for the best day care centers when the child is 9 months old."
Most of your friends are willing to face this once, Chen said, but not two.
Ours is the first generation with the highest standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, has attracted renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations that carry most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Prepared by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not speak of how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the global temperature increase that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process," said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 per cent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also encouraged talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, Friday presented the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated the talks last week.
United States Special Climate Envoy Todd Stern rejected the assertions calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared with volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is adopting a tougher line with China, with respect to what the Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs He Yafei said that the U.S. climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the major powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive trying to contain the major emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, Ulate said, who also works as a regional adviser on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants said that talks would produce a political agreement at the very least.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, drew up a preliminary treaty proposal of 24 pages early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and demand the action of emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most exceptional issues before the heads of government came to an end.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and rushed to the Bella Center corridors, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, to be able to delimit the claims that will be made during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where 13,000 people come in and out of the convention center every day, the guitar activists show night shows mocking the countries they think are selling, and preliminary proposals are hand-in-hand instead of mail), poses a challenge.
Intensity only builds: almost all key ministers are here at the moment, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the major leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for the global policy of International Conservation.
Heavy weights are coming.
The first train to 225 km from Britain redefines that feeling of Monday
At 5.13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will pierce the darkness to point out a train departure that marks a revolution for travel to Britain.
The country's first high-speed interurban train will reach 225 km, passing like a lightning from Ashford, Kent, to St Pancas station in London, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Secretary of Transport, will then join Lady Kelly Holmes on board the first Javelin interurban service outside London.
He expects the new service to finally connect Britain to an international network of fast, reliable trains and connect the large conurbations of the Midlands, North and Scotland to London.
The neglected remote areas would become prosperous suburbs, business travel times would shorten and the shift of planes and cars to the railway would reduce national emissions of coal, as would road congestion.
In theory, the three main political parties believe in this vision.
But the tens of billions of pounds that are needed to build a new national railway network, the inevitable battle of planning and fears about environmental damage, can still slow Britain's high-speed lines.
High Speed Two (HS2), a company created in January to provide the Government with a feasibility study, will deliver its report to Lord Adonis on December 30, according to the Times.
This will provide you with a detailed itinerary of the next phase planned for the high-speed network.
The new line linking London to the Midlands of the West will be drawn within a five-meter radius in urban areas and areas where the environmental impact can be controversial.
In rural areas, the plan will be drawn within a 25-metre radius of a final route.
HS2 is also expected to set three options for a wider high-speed network to the north.
Lord Adonis will respond in spring.
The preferred option that is being proposed is a Y-shaped configuration, in which a single high-speed line would reach the Midlands of the West.
The line would be divided into or near Birmingham, with a branch heading west from the Peninsulas to Manchester and Scotland, and another heading northeast to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
One line would enter Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the most beneficial option," said a railway member.
Once completed, travel times between London and Edinburgh would be reduced to 2 hours and 40 minutes.
The first section, which would not be inaugurated before 2025, would allow passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to just over one current hour.
The proposals would allow trains to travel to 402 kmh, turning the British network into the fastest in Europe.
The initial route is being designed to withstand trains of 400 mt in length, capable of transporting 1,100 people.
At least 18 trains could operate on a London-Birmingham line every hour.
This means that a London terminal would be needed to receive 20,000 passengers an hour.
Considering the restrictions on the space of the capital, an existing station is expected to be extended to fit the high-speed network.
Experts from the railway industry argue that only St Pancras International or Euston station offers that potential.
Lord Adonis will announce whether he believes the scheme should proceed, but a broad public consultation and planning procedures mean that no final decision will be taken until after a general election.
Even if the work starts, the network would have to be built in sections.
Trains would initially be forced to leave the fast lines on existing lanes north of Birmingham, maintaining travel times between London and Scotland over three hours.
This is seen as the crucial point needed to ensure a change of aircraft to trains, a point of reference for the railway revolution.
