Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the great French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is the question of employees joining the above-mentioned "values" as it was before to impose products on consumers thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to customers' preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end up in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives particularly.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive conduct and a prospective vision"; it requires employees to undertake a commitment that is totally opposed to the recommendations of an authoritative management.
For this reason, we called for a managerial revolution, which would be to put the collaborators at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion surveys have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange's questionnaire among his employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many rounds, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanical way.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old driving theory that the American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely disseminated behind them.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the commitment of the executives, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a position of mechanical management, inadequate to the world today.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, means adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into all reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is possible only if it appears clearly as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Reason Analysis adopt this conception of employees' motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company on the basis of a default dose that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resources management "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
