The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa Hallae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-metre-long, 1.50-metre-high animal that ran over the two strong hind legs, had an extended head with sharp teeth and curved curves, short arms with claws in the shape of a hook and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa Hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of Texas University in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry area of the Supercontinent Pangea in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in the north of New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for sediments of the Triassic, reports Randall Irmis a member of the team of the Utah Natural History Museum.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were assembled in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other experts in dinosaurs do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, comments for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time approximately 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these first dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, the experts discuss, for example, when the savouries were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: carnivorous teropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauros known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbivoros (sauri with bird pelvis), to which, for example, belong the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and his colleagues, Tawa Hallae is a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa found the researchers found signs of airbags, such as those that also possessed the offspring of the teropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa findae also the bones of the spine were evidently partially air-filled.
Tawa is the teropod with older and primitive air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the posterior giant sauropods also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, researchers conclude that the sauries arose there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lineages separated at first and spread from South America across all corners of the Earth, which by then still formed a unique earthly mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa the remains of two other teropods not closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single related predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migratory waves were given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science Study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, who belongs to a group of siblings of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, comments the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how the dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to Mesozoic dominant terrestrial vertebrates remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triásic the dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of the current crocodiles and the pterosauries and with many other saurios.
Towards the end of the Triásic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and developed many new species, while the kinship extinguished at the boundary of the Triásic towards the Jurassic.
Success stories weren't eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
It may have been given a massive extinction to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could defeat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact brakes the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
